(2) The nature of the ‘carmina’ of v. 17. What was Horace sending or professing to send? The usual answer has been, the-first three booles oftlze Odes; and there is much probability to be alleged for it, in respect of the importance of the occasion supposed, of Horace’s usual employment of the term ‘carmina ' when applied to his own writings ³⁵, of the plural ‘libellis ’ v. 4 (contrast ‘ libello ’ of the first book of Satires, Sat. 1. 10. 92), ‘fasciculum librorum’ v. 13, and generally of the date to which the Epistle is then referred. If, however, any more particular date is sought, difficulties arise. The Odes, we have every reason to believe, were given to the world in B.C. 23. Augustus did not leave Rome for Sicily and the East before the middle of Β. C. 22. Are we to imagine, then, that Horace's Odes were unknown to him for some months after their publication? or are we to look upon this as a formal presentation of a book which the poet already knew to be approved of?
